detailedReviews.author: Elizabeth Lyman Jensen
detailedReviews.text:
The food here was absolutely delicious and it was so fun to try new dishes with flavors I've never experienced before. The mango cucumber salad was a little too spicy for me (I'm rather wimpy when it comes to spice), so if you're one who wants only mild spices, you may want to skip the salad. However, between me and my cousins we sampled most of the dishes and sides on the menu and everything else was perfectly spiced for me and truly delicious. I especially enjoyed the street corn and the sweet potato wedges with the fry sauce and the mild piri piri sauce. The sauces were all so good!

Knowing that eating here also helps provide food to those in need is the icing on the cake and makes this restaurant an awesome choice in every way!

detailedReviews.author: Dallin Kimble
detailedReviews.text: Maybe 3.5 stars would be more accurate. We love the idea and there are some great restaurants like this in other cities (Nando's is a favorite). We ordered the meal for four people. Zulu's chicken was not fresh and really dry. The sweet potato fries were good and the side salad might have been the best part of our meal, but overall it was expensive for the pretty average meal we received.

detailedReviews.author: Lizzi Perkins
detailedReviews.text:
This is my new favorite place in Lehi. The food was delicious. I'm not usually a salad gal, but the salad was flavorful and amazing. Chicken and rice or chicken and salad usually all taste the same, but this had unique flavors and the piri piri sauce is to die for.

They were pretty quick, had indoor and outdoor seating, served food on sturdy plates instead of flimsy plastic or styrofoam, and I was able to hang out and chat with my friend for as long as we wanted.

So many items on their menu are gluten free (and having celiac there is no cross contamination which is a win). Would definitely recommend to anyone open to trying a new fast-casual place!

I recently tried the grilled cheese and gumbo combo too, and it was really solid. Unique flavors, great portions, and fast-casual vibes. Prices are affordable. Definitely worth checking out!

detailedReviews.author: Pat Kay
detailedReviews.text: Wow. Never again. Showed up after going to Thanksgiving Point. Had 6 thirsty children with us. And they had NO WATER. They claimed manager was gone so they weren‚Äôt able to give us water. They said the water in the back isn‚Äôt drinkable. So how do they wash the cucumbers and the lettuce and all the veggies? Do they use non-drinkable water? GROSS.Or do they not wash it? Also GROSS.  We know it‚Äôs illegal for them to not provide free water. Plus it immoral to charge us $45 for three children and one adult and then try to insist we also buy bottled water at $2 when, by law, they must provide drinkable free water. They were worthless in trying to remedy a situation that they created by having no drinkable water in the place. They failed to offer soda as an option and just kept insisting we pay more. Well hope they enjoyed that $$$ today cause they won‚Äôt be getting any more from me or the friends that were with me today.

detailedReviews.author: Russell deJesus
detailedReviews.text: Great employees, great business model, great food. Walking in, the door was heavy and hard to open. There is a big poster of what the LLC's mission is and where their donations go. They have a giant menu above where you order, or you could take a more portable menu from the front. There are few menu items, which I prefer because I don't like getting cognitive fatigue from choosing from too many items. There is a scale for choosing the spiciness of the piri piri, and all of the sauces are delicious. So far, we've had kids meal chicken strips, tricolor potatoes, yellow rice, cucumber salad (my favorite side of all time), piri piri wrap, and piri piri chicken salad. No complaints about any of them. The 5 stars were well-deserved! Thank you for your charity work, employee training, and your food!
